The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Spentex industries Ltd has picked up a 6.77 per cent stake in Amit Spinning Industries Ltd for around Rs 3 crore, taking its total stake in the company to 50.91 per cent. Spentex had earlier made an open offer to the shareholders of Amit Spinning to acquire about 82 lakh equity shares of the company, representing a 20 per cent stake, at Rs 11 per share. 

 Edelweiss Capital has completed a qualified institutional placement (QIP) of Rs 46.59 crore for Spentex Industries Ltd. According to a company release, this is the first QIP by an Indian company after the fresh guidelines from Sebi to qualified institutional buyers in May, 2006. 

 Singapore-based Ascott group has signed a master development agreement with Chennai-based Rattha group to acquire and develop seven properties in India by 2010. Under the agreement, Assott will manage the properties for 10 years with an option to renew the contract for another 10 years.

 Toyota Kirloskar Motor has introduced an apprentice-training initiative The Toyota Technical Education Programme (T-TEP). The programme is a training module aimed at enhancing the skill sets and employability of the ITI students in the 15-18 years age group. 

 NTPC Ltd has signed an MoU with Singareni Collieries Company for a joint venture in coal and power. The joint venture company will acquire coal mines and lignite mines, develop them and sell the final products at home and abroad.

 Thomas Cook (India) Ltds profit for the third quarter of the current fiscal was Rs 10 crore against Rs 8.5 crore a year ago, an increase of 17 per cent. Revenues rose 42 per cent to Rs 47.6 crore from Rs 33.4 crore in the previous year. 

 Hidesign has launched a travel bag Alamo. The product is available in shades of black, brown and tan and have a price tag of Rs 8,195.

 BEA Systems and Tata Consultancy Services (TCS) will develop service oriented architecture (SOA) solutions based on the BEA AquaLogic and WebLogic platforms. 

 Prince Plastics International has launched Click-N-Seal, an airtight food preservation system. The product is part of the umbrella brand Princeware, and is available in the range of Rs 70 to Rs 500.

 Hindustan Lever (HLL) has launched Fair amp; Lovely Menz active in Bengal. The product is available in 25 and 50 gram packs for Rs 30 and Rs 53 respectively.

